WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:04.667
♪

00:05.750 --> 00:09.333
♪

00:09.333 --> 00:12.291
JOHN: I know you all have busy
lives, what with college,

00:12.291 --> 00:16.000
and having a family,
and your "art."

00:16.000 --> 00:17.583
But I’m glad you’re all here

00:17.583 --> 00:19.709
for your last New Year’s Eve.

00:19.709 --> 00:21.083
"Last"?

00:21.083 --> 00:22.458
What, are you going
to murder us all?

00:22.458 --> 00:23.667
(laughing)

00:23.667 --> 00:24.750
JOAN: No!

00:24.750 --> 00:26.792
He thinks the world
is going to end.

00:26.792 --> 00:28.750
It is! In three hours,

00:28.750 --> 00:31.125
the Y2K bug
is going to bite,

00:31.125 --> 00:32.125
and it’s going to hurt

00:32.125 --> 00:34.125
like when a wasp
gets you in the penis.

00:34.125 --> 00:36.125
Okay, Daddy, well, we’ll
hang around for a little while,

00:36.125 --> 00:37.917
but then we got to get our dates
to our party.

00:37.917 --> 00:39.709
They were extras
in that<i> 90210 </i>episode

00:39.709 --> 00:41.625
where Brenda and Kelly
wore the same dress to prom.

00:41.625 --> 00:43.458
JOAN: Oh, that’s the episode
where Brenda

00:43.458 --> 00:45.542
loses her virginity to Dylan!

00:45.542 --> 00:47.375
She never should have done that.

00:47.375 --> 00:49.125
That was a big mistake.

00:49.125 --> 00:50.667
Hey, speaking of mistakes,

00:50.667 --> 00:52.417
we should really
be getting Tyler home.

00:52.417 --> 00:53.625
Are you not listening to me?

00:53.625 --> 00:55.417
It’s Y2K.

00:55.417 --> 00:57.542
It’s not safe for you
to go outside.

00:57.542 --> 00:58.917
TIM: Yeah, at the hospital
they told us

00:58.917 --> 01:00.208
that if the computers crash,

01:00.208 --> 01:01.667
then the stoplights
could go down,

01:01.667 --> 01:02.667
and it’d be mass chaos.

01:02.667 --> 01:05.291
HEATHER: Well, at least
we have a real doctor here

01:05.291 --> 01:07.250
in the house
with us tonight.

01:07.250 --> 01:09.125
He’s a medical student.

01:09.125 --> 01:10.500
But don’t worry,

01:10.500 --> 01:12.250
as patronizer of this family,

01:12.250 --> 01:14.375
it’s my role to protect you all,

01:14.375 --> 01:16.208
and I’m ready for the worst.

01:16.208 --> 01:18.125
-I think you mean "patriarch."
HEATHER: See, Dad?

01:18.125 --> 01:20.333
I told you,
he is really, really smart.

01:20.333 --> 01:22.375
Not smart enough
to use a condom.

01:23.917 --> 01:25.583
Good thing I had 50.

01:25.583 --> 01:27.792
♪

01:27.792 --> 01:28.917
GREG: A generator?

01:28.917 --> 01:30.792
Don’t you think
that’s a little paranoid?

01:30.792 --> 01:32.375
I am not paranoid.

01:32.375 --> 01:34.250
Here, take this marker

01:34.250 --> 01:35.750
and write your blood type
on your arm.

01:37.208 --> 01:38.917
By the way, I saw Dad
siphoning that gas

01:38.917 --> 01:41.166
-out of your car earlier.
-What?

01:41.166 --> 01:42.792
Dad, where’d you get that gas?

01:42.792 --> 01:44.417
Hmm?

01:44.417 --> 01:46.166
I found it.

01:46.166 --> 01:48.583
HEATHER: You took out $17,000?

01:48.583 --> 01:50.000
JOHN:
Better to have it in our wall

01:50.000 --> 01:52.834
than in an ATM machine
when the banks go offline.

01:52.834 --> 01:55.000
You know, you don’t
have to say "ATM machine,"

01:55.000 --> 01:57.709
because the M in ATM
stands for "machine,"

01:57.709 --> 01:59.792
so when you say "ATM machine"

01:59.792 --> 02:02.125
you’re really just saying
"machine" twice.

02:02.125 --> 02:04.083
HEATHER: See, Dad?
Isn’t Tim clever?

02:04.083 --> 02:05.959
Not clever enough
to wear a condom.

02:05.959 --> 02:08.458
♪

02:08.458 --> 02:10.583
All right, the left jug
is for drinking,

02:10.583 --> 02:13.083
and the right jug
is for peeing.

02:13.083 --> 02:14.959
Our left or your left?

02:14.959 --> 02:16.000
Oh.

02:16.000 --> 02:17.083
-Mom?
-Yeah?

02:17.083 --> 02:18.667
Where did those girls go?

02:18.667 --> 02:21.625
Oh, they said the party
wasn’t very jiggy and they left.

02:21.625 --> 02:23.834
What! No!

02:23.834 --> 02:26.375
I’ve got Cindy’s ChapStick,
that was gonna be my in.

02:26.375 --> 02:29.083
Ohhh, is Greg in a mood?

02:29.083 --> 02:30.166
Stop it, Heather.

02:30.166 --> 02:31.709
JOAN: Yes, Greg’s in a mood.

02:31.709 --> 02:34.166
I am not in a mood, Mom! Gosh!

02:34.166 --> 02:35.375
Ooh, it’s almost midnight.

02:35.375 --> 02:37.041
Hey Greg, why don’t you
join us over here?

02:37.041 --> 02:39.083
I don’t know,
why don’t you take a guess?

02:39.083 --> 02:40.792
Maybe it’s because
I don’t wanna.

02:40.792 --> 02:42.041
He didn’t give me time
to guess.

02:42.041 --> 02:43.917
Yeah, no, just ignore him.

02:43.917 --> 02:46.125
All right, you guys,
come on, ball’s gonna drop!

02:46.125 --> 02:47.208
MAN:<i> All right, America.</i>

02:47.208 --> 02:49.125
<i>Get ready to say goodbye</i>
<i>to 1999!</i>

02:49.125 --> 02:51.875
TOGETHER: Ten! Nine!

02:51.875 --> 02:55.333
Eight! Seven! Six!

02:55.333 --> 02:56.875
Do you think anything bad’s
going to happen?

02:56.875 --> 02:58.166
If it does,
the scariest thing is that

02:58.166 --> 02:59.917
we’re living in a world
where my dad is right

02:59.917 --> 03:01.625
and we were wrong.

03:01.625 --> 03:04.166
TOGETHER: Two! One!

03:04.166 --> 03:05.375
-Happy new year!
-Happy new year!

03:05.375 --> 03:07.166
(cheering)

03:07.166 --> 03:09.125
HEATHER: Oh.

03:09.125 --> 03:10.333
It’s Y2K.

03:10.333 --> 03:12.250
Dad was right.

03:12.250 --> 03:13.500
Call me John!

03:13.500 --> 03:14.542
(gun cocks)

03:14.542 --> 03:15.917
Oh!

03:15.917 --> 03:17.125
JOHN: Let’s go.

03:17.125 --> 03:18.583
TIM: I got your six, John!

03:18.583 --> 03:20.625
♪

03:20.625 --> 03:22.417
Everybody start
boarding up the windows

03:22.417 --> 03:24.500
before the looters get here.

03:24.500 --> 03:26.250
-Um, honey?
-Hmm?

03:26.250 --> 03:28.542
If there’s a worldwide
power outage,

03:28.542 --> 03:31.041
why are we the only ones
without power?

03:31.041 --> 03:33.959
Hmm, there’s a lot less chaos
than I expected.

03:33.959 --> 03:35.875
But I’m still going
to shoot my shotgun.

03:37.500 --> 03:39.250
Do you guys smell
something burning?

03:39.250 --> 03:41.125
(sniffing)

03:41.125 --> 03:42.542
TIM: Oh! Fire!

03:42.542 --> 03:45.375
(spraying)

03:45.375 --> 03:47.333
JOHN: My generator knocked out
the power.

03:47.333 --> 03:48.834
HEATHER: Oh, wait, Dad!

03:48.834 --> 03:50.709
Isn’t that where
we hid the money?

03:50.709 --> 03:52.875
JOHN: My $17,000!

03:52.875 --> 03:55.750
$17,000?!

03:55.750 --> 03:57.709
Good job, Timmy.

03:57.709 --> 03:58.959
HEATHER: Babe,
you were pretty hot

03:58.959 --> 04:00.417
putting out that fire.

04:00.417 --> 04:01.500
Yeah, that’s right.

04:01.500 --> 04:02.667
You’re a real hero.

04:02.667 --> 04:05.000
-Dr. Tim Hughes.
HEATHER: That’s right.

04:05.000 --> 04:06.625
-Oh, God, that scared me.
-Okay!

04:06.625 --> 04:07.917
Don’t--it’s okay.

04:09.917 --> 04:12.208
JOHN: I guess I was hoping
that Y2K happened

04:12.208 --> 04:14.542
so that everybody
would have to move back home,

04:14.542 --> 04:18.125
and we could be like we were
before they left us.

04:18.125 --> 04:22.291
How about we have
a weekly brunch,

04:22.291 --> 04:27.041
and we lure everyone here
with plates of free food.

04:27.041 --> 04:28.291
How about that?

04:28.291 --> 04:31.166
Okay, well,
but if that doesn’t work,

04:31.166 --> 04:33.166
there’s always
the Mayan apocalypse

04:33.166 --> 04:35.041
of 2012, huh?

04:35.041 --> 04:37.333
Yes, there’s that
to look forward to.

04:37.333 --> 04:39.667
-Yeah.
-And our grandchild.

04:39.667 --> 04:44.041
Sweet Tyler, he’s going
to be a millennial.

04:44.041 --> 04:46.417
The best generation yet.

04:46.417 --> 04:48.542
♪

04:49.959 --> 04:54.709
♪

04:54.709 --> 04:56.208
HEATHER: Okay,
so it’s a C-section,

04:56.208 --> 04:57.458
I’ll be in the hospital
three days.

04:57.458 --> 04:59.750
5:00 to 5:30,
organic meal time,

04:59.750 --> 05:01.917
5:30 to 6:00,

05:01.917 --> 05:03.333
classical music.

05:03.333 --> 05:05.959
And then I like to end the day
with a little bit of fun.

05:05.959 --> 05:08.709
Oh, well, at least
the evening ends with some fun.

05:08.709 --> 05:09.875
Yeah, and obviously FUN

05:09.875 --> 05:11.792
is Fundamentals
in Understanding Numbers.

05:13.917 --> 05:16.458
I should have been around more
when you were a kid.

05:16.458 --> 05:18.417
There’s my little angels!

05:18.417 --> 05:20.834
<i>Bonjour,</i>
Mom-Mom and Pop-Pop!

05:20.834 --> 05:22.792
Look, I built a feeling!

05:22.792 --> 05:24.792
Oh, isn’t that pretty!

05:24.792 --> 05:26.959
Yeah, and ugly.

05:26.959 --> 05:29.458
We apply a negative word
to counterbalance

05:29.458 --> 05:31.166
every positive one,
so the kids see

05:31.166 --> 05:32.750
that there’s beauty in failure.

05:32.750 --> 05:34.750
Oh, that’s so wonderful!

05:35.750 --> 05:36.500
And stupid.

05:37.959 --> 05:39.333
Did I do it right?

05:39.333 --> 05:40.917
(chuckling)

05:40.917 --> 05:43.041
Five miles!

05:43.041 --> 05:45.750
Or roughly the length
of the new Coldplay album.

05:45.750 --> 05:47.542
Ah, that sea breeze
running through the old pony

05:47.542 --> 05:48.625
sure feels good.

05:48.625 --> 05:50.125
So you took a run
right before

05:50.125 --> 05:52.000
your wife’s having
your third baby?

05:52.000 --> 05:53.709
TIM: Yeah, if I don’t exercise,
I start thinking.

05:53.709 --> 05:55.250
I start thinking,
I start feeling.

05:55.250 --> 05:57.166
I start feeling,
I start eating.

05:57.166 --> 05:58.375
Nobody wants that.

05:58.375 --> 06:00.542
JOHN: Well, the fastest
my heart’s gonna beat today

06:00.542 --> 06:03.625
is when I’m watching
<i>Wheel of Fortune.</i>

06:03.625 --> 06:06.792
Oh, that’s right,
you public radio types

06:06.792 --> 06:08.500
don’t have TV, eh?

06:08.500 --> 06:11.709
HEATHER: Ugh, no Dad,
TV is the lazy parents’ crutch.

06:11.709 --> 06:15.000
We like our imaginations
to be the screen.

06:15.000 --> 06:17.709
All right, kiddos,
time to go brush those teeth!

06:17.709 --> 06:19.375
SAMANTHA:
Yay! Longest brush wins!

06:19.375 --> 06:21.208
Oh, you’re going down!

06:21.208 --> 06:22.750
But our teeth
are the real winners.

06:22.750 --> 06:24.333
-Yeah!
-Ah!

06:24.333 --> 06:25.750
Can’t wait to add another.

06:25.750 --> 06:28.625
Oh, I know, babe, they really
are such blessings.

06:29.417 --> 06:30.750
(baby crying)

06:30.750 --> 06:33.041
(kids arguing)

06:33.041 --> 06:35.417
Tim, the other two
did not cry like this!

06:35.417 --> 06:36.709
Sophia is broken!

06:36.709 --> 06:38.250
She is a broken baby!

06:38.250 --> 06:40.291
No, no, the doctor
said it’s colic.

06:40.291 --> 06:42.417
It’ll stop
in like four months.

06:42.417 --> 06:44.709
We cannot endure
four months of this crap!

06:44.709 --> 06:46.458
TYLER: Help!

06:46.458 --> 06:47.667
SAMANTHA: Eat blocks, nerd!

06:47.667 --> 06:49.458
-Knock it off, nerd!
-Tim!

06:49.458 --> 06:51.041
-Mom!
-Samantha!

06:51.041 --> 06:53.458
You know that is not
how we resolve conflict,

06:53.458 --> 06:55.750
we raise our hearts,
we lower our voices.

06:55.750 --> 06:57.166
You don’t care about me anymore!

06:57.166 --> 06:59.000
You just care
about your new baby!

06:59.000 --> 07:00.625
You got that right!

07:00.625 --> 07:03.375
-Oh, no, you didn’t!
-Oh, my God, Tim,

07:03.375 --> 07:04.667
we are losing it!

07:04.667 --> 07:06.709
They are expressing
anger and aggression

07:06.709 --> 07:09.083
verbally for the first time.

07:09.083 --> 07:11.875
Well, it’s probably
because they haven’t exercised!

07:11.875 --> 07:13.417
I know that’s my problem.

07:13.417 --> 07:15.375
I mean, if only
there was something

07:15.375 --> 07:17.041
that could entertain them,

07:17.041 --> 07:19.333
you know,
while I go for a run.

07:19.333 --> 07:21.250
Oh, dude, we are so not caving!

07:21.250 --> 07:22.291
No TV!

07:22.291 --> 07:24.375
We’re not going to have
wide-eyed zombie kids.

07:24.375 --> 07:25.500
What, what’s gonna happen next?

07:25.500 --> 07:27.250
They’re going to stop making
their own almond milk?

07:27.250 --> 07:28.834
Oh, please,
if they’re growing the almonds

07:28.834 --> 07:30.125
they’re going to make the milk.

07:30.125 --> 07:31.834
Oh, I have an idea.

07:31.834 --> 07:35.000
We get Matt
to entertain those two

07:35.000 --> 07:36.417
so we can have a break.

07:36.417 --> 07:37.333
We can’t do that!

07:37.333 --> 07:38.875
Matt’s not gonna
babysit our kids!

07:38.875 --> 07:40.500
He’s a cool artist!

07:40.500 --> 07:42.709
He lives in a loft,
his bed is a loft!

07:42.709 --> 07:44.291
It’s all lofts over there!

07:44.291 --> 07:46.375
(rock music)

07:46.375 --> 07:53.291
♪

07:57.333 --> 07:59.458
This song
is blowing my mind!

07:59.458 --> 08:01.458
I can’t believe we’ve been
listening to Wagner

08:01.458 --> 08:03.125
for five years.

08:03.125 --> 08:06.792
Why do you get the kids’ cups
and we get the grown-up cups?

08:06.792 --> 08:10.208
Because good things come
in small packages, like you.

08:10.208 --> 08:11.542
WAITRESS:
Here you go, sweetie.

08:11.542 --> 08:14.041
What kind of fruit is this?

08:14.041 --> 08:15.417
You’ve never had
French fries before?

08:18.709 --> 08:20.917
-No, Tim, no!
-Don’t you do it!

08:20.917 --> 08:22.417
Oh, no, you can’t go
down that road,

08:22.417 --> 08:23.917
once you start you won’t
be able to get back.

08:23.917 --> 08:25.917
You have an obsessive
personality, babe.

08:25.917 --> 08:28.041
I’m just so stressed out.

08:28.041 --> 08:30.083
I haven’t been this tempted
since my bachelor party.

08:31.583 --> 08:34.208
I still dream about that buffet.

08:34.208 --> 08:37.125
Wait a minute,
wait a minute.

08:37.125 --> 08:38.625
She stopped crying,
we did it.

08:38.625 --> 08:40.583
No, I just turned down
the monitor.

08:40.583 --> 08:42.250
I couldn’t stand it anymore.

08:42.250 --> 08:43.917
MATT: Hey, we’re home!

08:43.917 --> 08:45.166
TYLER: Mom, guess what!

08:45.166 --> 08:47.250
Turns out we’re not
allergic to soda!

08:48.250 --> 08:51.083
Okay, that’s good.

08:51.083 --> 08:52.291
MATT: You all right, Timmy?

08:52.291 --> 08:53.375
No, Matt.

08:53.375 --> 08:55.041
(Heather groaning)

08:55.041 --> 08:58.500
Our lives are spinning
out of control, Mom.

08:58.500 --> 09:01.125
Tim has lost so much hair
there’s hardly any ponytail

09:01.125 --> 09:03.542
there to grab onto
when we’re making love.

09:03.542 --> 09:06.417
Well, honey, you have
a difficult baby,

09:06.417 --> 09:08.583
and that changes
the family dynamic.

09:08.583 --> 09:11.458
I should know,
I had a difficult one, too.

09:11.458 --> 09:13.500
-Greg?
-No.

09:13.500 --> 09:14.709
-Matt?
-No.

09:16.250 --> 09:17.000
Yes.

09:18.250 --> 09:21.125
You were a little monster.

09:21.125 --> 09:24.291
But as my wise mother
once said to me,

09:24.291 --> 09:27.583
"I’ve already done this crap,
you figure it out."

09:29.000 --> 09:32.709
♪

09:32.709 --> 09:35.458
Giving up is so good.

09:35.458 --> 09:37.250
Yeah, we should have
done this years go.

09:37.250 --> 09:38.542
Principles are for losers.

09:40.083 --> 09:41.166
(explosion)

09:41.166 --> 09:43.208
I’ve never seen a head explode
like that before,

09:43.208 --> 09:44.417
and I’m a doctor.

09:44.417 --> 09:45.792
(laughing)

09:47.583 --> 09:49.583
(laughing)

09:49.583 --> 09:51.542
I only saw Marty throw up,

09:51.542 --> 09:53.208
I didn’t realize
they both did.

09:53.208 --> 09:55.583
-Hey, Greg.
-What--what else did Meemaw say?

09:57.959 --> 10:03.083
♪

10:03.083 --> 10:04.625
Ta-da!

10:04.625 --> 10:05.834
Honey, you didn’t
have to do this

10:05.834 --> 10:07.333
all the way from the elevator.

10:07.333 --> 10:08.417
Of course, I did.

10:08.417 --> 10:10.041
We’re married now,
this is how you’re gonna get

10:10.041 --> 10:11.834
from place to place.

10:11.834 --> 10:13.458
Well, I guess it does kind of
make up for the fact

10:13.458 --> 10:14.750
that you look like
a jack-o’-lantern

10:14.750 --> 10:16.250
-during our wedding.
-Well, I told you,

10:16.250 --> 10:18.208
being married to
a ping-pong champion

10:18.208 --> 10:20.875
is not easy.

10:20.875 --> 10:22.500
(giggling)

10:22.500 --> 10:23.792
Aw, honey.

10:23.792 --> 10:25.166
That is so sweet.

10:25.166 --> 10:26.500
Thank you.

10:26.500 --> 10:28.125
Oh, I didn’t do it.

10:28.125 --> 10:29.083
What?

10:31.625 --> 10:33.750
"May all of your nights together

10:33.750 --> 10:35.875
be as romantic as this one.

10:35.875 --> 10:38.500
Enjoy each other
in every way."

10:38.500 --> 10:39.750
From the hotel?

10:39.750 --> 10:40.792
That’s kind of creepy.

10:40.792 --> 10:42.291
"Love, Mom."

10:42.291 --> 10:44.709
Oh, wow, okay,
that’s even creepier.

10:44.709 --> 10:46.291
I wonder which mom it was.

10:46.291 --> 10:49.959
I’m going to guess the one
who cut in on our first dance.

10:49.959 --> 10:52.417
But it’s just,
like, a random guess.

10:52.417 --> 10:54.375
GREG: Mom, you and Dad
have always been proof

10:54.375 --> 10:56.709
of what a great marriage can be.

10:56.709 --> 10:58.458
Yeah, I know,
she did look beautiful,

10:58.458 --> 11:00.417
and she just nailed that
"Chattanooga Choo-Choo,"

11:00.417 --> 11:02.125
didn’t she?

11:02.125 --> 11:04.041
Yeah, no, I’m lucky
to be her husband.

11:04.041 --> 11:06.291
Greg.

11:06.291 --> 11:08.667
Well, I think it’s very nice
that they paid

11:08.667 --> 11:11.000
for the rehearsal dinner.

11:11.000 --> 11:12.834
Well, Mom, they’re trying.

11:13.750 --> 11:14.792
Greg.

11:14.792 --> 11:16.750
(laughing)

11:16.750 --> 11:18.667
I only saw Marty throw up.

11:18.667 --> 11:20.333
I didn’t realize they both did.

11:20.333 --> 11:21.333
Hey, Greg.

11:21.333 --> 11:23.250
What--what else did Meemaw say?

11:23.250 --> 11:25.417
Greg, aren’t you forgetting
about someone else here?

11:25.417 --> 11:27.709
Oh, yeah, hey Mom,
Jen says hi.

11:27.709 --> 11:30.792
All right, well,
I love you too.

11:30.792 --> 11:31.875
No, I love you.

11:31.875 --> 11:33.208
No, you... ow!

11:33.208 --> 11:34.959
What?

11:34.959 --> 11:37.125
(sighing)

11:37.125 --> 11:40.792
Mom, I’m going to have to call
you back in two minutes.

11:40.792 --> 11:43.875
♪

11:43.875 --> 11:46.125
It has been great seeing
all of our friends and family,

11:46.125 --> 11:47.417
but I am so tired

11:47.417 --> 11:49.208
of hearing everyone’s
marriage advice.

11:49.208 --> 11:50.834
I know, I’m, like,
starting to get angry

11:50.834 --> 11:52.625
that I’m not allowed
to go to bed angry, you know.

11:52.625 --> 11:54.792
Well, all we got to do
is go to one more brunch,

11:54.792 --> 11:57.709
and then Mr. and Mrs. Short
are on a flight to Bora Bora.

11:57.709 --> 11:59.000
Mm, Mrs. Short.

11:59.000 --> 12:01.500
I like the sound of that.

12:01.500 --> 12:02.667
Speaking of which,

12:02.667 --> 12:04.542
the other Mrs. Short
wants to stop by our house

12:04.542 --> 12:06.333
real quick to say goodbye
before we leave.

12:06.333 --> 12:07.458
Is that cool?

12:07.458 --> 12:09.709
Um, actually, honey,

12:09.709 --> 12:11.667
you know I love your mom.

12:11.667 --> 12:13.333
And I mean really love her.

12:13.333 --> 12:16.417
It just--it feels a little bit
like she’s kind of

12:16.417 --> 12:19.500
up in our business a lot,
especially lately.

12:19.500 --> 12:21.250
Does it feel that way to you?

12:21.250 --> 12:22.750
I don’t know.

12:22.750 --> 12:24.250
I mean, I can ask her.
You want me to ask her?

12:24.250 --> 12:26.917
Oh, no, no, no, no, no, no.
Definitely don’t do that.

12:26.917 --> 12:30.959
What I think it is, is I think
that now that you’re mine,

12:30.959 --> 12:34.875
she’s just having a hard time
passing that Greg torch.

12:34.875 --> 12:36.750
Honey, come here.

12:36.750 --> 12:39.000
I’m yours, all right?

12:39.000 --> 12:41.125
Yours, only,
forever and ever.

12:41.125 --> 12:42.667
-I promise, okay?
-Okay.

12:44.667 --> 12:46.166
This is all really flattering.

12:46.166 --> 12:48.834
I’ve never had two women
fight over me before.

12:48.834 --> 12:51.291
Ah, honey,
that’s not what this is.

12:51.291 --> 12:53.542
Mmm.

12:53.542 --> 12:55.583
All right, honey, you take care
of the contraceptives,

12:55.583 --> 12:57.542
I’ll take care
of the antacids.

12:58.917 --> 12:59.709
Greg?

13:02.125 --> 13:03.458
Honey?

13:03.458 --> 13:04.250
Greg?

13:05.709 --> 13:07.250
-Jen!
-Oh.

13:07.250 --> 13:09.417
JOAN: Hi, I’m just finishing up.

13:09.417 --> 13:10.709
Would you tell Greg

13:10.709 --> 13:13.291
I packed him three pairs
of underwear a day.

13:13.291 --> 13:16.166
An everyday pair,
a romantic pair, and a whoopsie.

13:18.083 --> 13:19.417
"A whoopsie."

13:19.417 --> 13:20.375
Oh, my God.

13:20.375 --> 13:22.375
♪

13:22.375 --> 13:23.875
JEN: Hey, uh, Greg,

13:23.875 --> 13:26.041
your mom is packing
your suitcase.

13:26.041 --> 13:27.750
Yeah?

13:27.750 --> 13:28.792
For our honeymoon.

13:28.792 --> 13:31.166
GREG: Yeah,
she’s really good at it.

13:31.166 --> 13:33.792
She’s got amazing
spatial relations.

13:33.792 --> 13:36.208
She once put
a whole Thanksgiving dinner

13:36.208 --> 13:38.083
into my lunch bag.

13:38.083 --> 13:39.083
Cool, cool.

13:39.083 --> 13:41.417
Hey, honey, can I talk to you
in the other room for a minute?

13:41.417 --> 13:44.041
Just very quickly,
very, very almost urgently?

13:46.500 --> 13:49.333
Wife’s already got
the nagging thing down I see.

13:49.333 --> 13:51.834
Dad, not cool.

13:53.083 --> 13:54.709
God, this is 2011.

13:55.750 --> 13:56.917
What’s up?

13:56.917 --> 13:59.834
Um, okay, look, this has gone
too far, all right?

13:59.834 --> 14:01.667
I’m sorry, but your mom,
she needs to stop.

14:01.667 --> 14:04.959
You need to pack your own
suitcase for your honeymoon.

14:04.959 --> 14:06.458
Honey, what is the big deal,
all right?

14:06.458 --> 14:07.667
It makes her happy.

14:07.667 --> 14:09.709
Yes, but, you’re my man now,

14:09.709 --> 14:14.000
and as my man, I just,
I need you to be your own man.

14:14.000 --> 14:16.083
Hey look, I get it.

14:16.083 --> 14:18.750
Married men
pack their own suitcases.

14:18.750 --> 14:20.208
All men do.

14:20.208 --> 14:25.709
♪

14:25.709 --> 14:30.250
Hi, Short, we reserved
a table by the water.

14:30.250 --> 14:33.375
I’m so sorry, we’re not going
to be able to seat you.

14:33.375 --> 14:35.166
Why?

14:35.166 --> 14:38.166
We require all men
to wear a collared shirt.

14:38.166 --> 14:40.625
And pants.

14:40.625 --> 14:41.834
And shoes.

14:41.834 --> 14:43.709
But I’m wearing shoes.
Sea shoes.

14:46.083 --> 14:47.625
JEN: Do you think you could
just make an exception

14:47.625 --> 14:48.917
this one time?

14:48.917 --> 14:51.750
You see, he packed his own
suitcase for the first time,

14:51.750 --> 14:53.333
and while he may have
forgotten, you know,

14:53.333 --> 14:56.959
a few things,
I really am very proud of him.

14:56.959 --> 14:59.208
My mom used to pack for me.

14:59.959 --> 15:02.291
Oh, I see.

15:02.291 --> 15:04.208
Well, good job, buddy!

15:04.208 --> 15:07.834
Here, let me get you
a placemat and some crayons.

15:07.834 --> 15:10.291
We have a fish tank
you’re gonna love.

15:10.291 --> 15:11.375
Does she think I’m--

15:11.375 --> 15:13.875
Just go with it,
I need a drink.

15:16.667 --> 15:18.542
MATT: I’m sorry, are you Will?

15:18.542 --> 15:19.792
Yeah, man, yeah.

15:19.792 --> 15:21.917
Hey, if there’s a Will,
there’s a way, okay?

15:21.917 --> 15:23.875
Out of her apartment
before she wakes up.

15:23.875 --> 15:24.917
(laughing)

15:27.583 --> 15:33.083
♪

15:33.083 --> 15:34.667
JOAN: Knock-knock!

15:34.667 --> 15:37.834
Chicken soup for
the emotionally wrecked soul.

15:37.834 --> 15:38.917
Thanks, Mom.

15:38.917 --> 15:40.834
JOAN: Honey, why don’t
we ask your dad

15:40.834 --> 15:42.458
for a pair of his pajamas,

15:42.458 --> 15:44.667
and that way you can
keep this outfit fresh

15:44.667 --> 15:46.959
for any job interviews
you might want to go on?

15:46.959 --> 15:48.500
Oh, no, Mom, I’m an artist.

15:48.500 --> 15:50.917
I’m not gonna go on any
job interviews for the man.

15:50.917 --> 15:53.959
Honey, I think you’re
too white to say that.

15:53.959 --> 15:55.166
Don’t tell Dad that I’m in here.

15:55.166 --> 15:56.542
Or anybody else.

15:56.542 --> 15:58.917
That I’m sleeping in the garage,
and I’ve lost everything.

15:58.917 --> 16:00.667
They all predicted that
I was going to be a failure,

16:00.667 --> 16:03.583
and I just--I’m going
to wait as long as possible

16:03.583 --> 16:04.750
before telling them,

16:04.750 --> 16:07.125
or at least until Greg
flips another golf cart.

16:08.250 --> 16:10.083
JOHN: Great brunch, Joanie.

16:10.083 --> 16:11.333
And save some of that meat.

16:11.333 --> 16:13.542
I’m going to put it
in my traps.

16:13.542 --> 16:15.375
JOAN: You’re setting traps?
What for?

16:15.375 --> 16:17.000
JOHN: Well, there’s
some kind of critter

16:17.000 --> 16:18.625
rummaging around in my garage.

16:18.625 --> 16:20.500
If the traps don’t work,

16:20.500 --> 16:22.709
I’m going to get myself
a pet owl.

16:22.709 --> 16:24.750
Although I might
do that anyway.

16:24.750 --> 16:26.041
Hey, where are Matt and Bonnie?

16:26.041 --> 16:27.417
Were we allowed to skip this?

16:27.417 --> 16:30.083
Knowing her, she probably
took all his money and ran off.

16:30.083 --> 16:33.083
Oh, I wish I could just call
them and say, "Wake up!

16:33.083 --> 16:34.834
Wake up!"

16:34.834 --> 16:37.000
Mom, why are you yelling?

16:37.000 --> 16:38.667
-Am I?
MATT: Ow!

16:38.667 --> 16:40.625
My trap!

16:40.625 --> 16:42.500
Don’t worry,
I got the humane kind.

16:42.500 --> 16:45.583
Although now that I think
about it, I may not have.

16:45.583 --> 16:47.208
(Matt muttering)

16:49.208 --> 16:51.917
MATT: Oh, good,
everyone’s here to see this.

16:51.917 --> 16:53.375
JOHN: Matt, take that off.

16:53.375 --> 16:56.083
That was supposed to catch
the critter living in my garage.

16:56.834 --> 16:57.750
MATT: It did.

17:00.083 --> 17:02.500
Yeah, no, Mom,
I--I can’t tell them.

17:02.500 --> 17:03.834
Could you, please?

17:03.834 --> 17:04.917
Yeah.

17:04.917 --> 17:07.041
Um, Bonnie left him, but...

17:08.792 --> 17:09.834
...she took all his money.

17:10.875 --> 17:12.125
But his art...

17:13.250 --> 17:15.083
...is a bust.

17:15.083 --> 17:15.959
But!

17:17.291 --> 17:19.125
He’s homeless.

17:19.125 --> 17:21.333
MATT: Wow, thank you, Mom.

17:21.333 --> 17:23.834
I don’t think this could get
any more humiliating.

17:23.834 --> 17:26.959
Matt, honey, I am so sorry.

17:26.959 --> 17:29.166
And your fly is down.

17:31.000 --> 17:37.917
♪

17:40.792 --> 17:43.875
-What’s all this?
JOHN: Oh!

17:43.875 --> 17:47.375
Well, I figured if you didn’t
want to move up to your bedroom,

17:47.375 --> 17:49.667
I’d move the bedroom
down to you.

17:49.667 --> 17:51.375
Dad, this is all Greg’s stuff.

17:51.375 --> 17:54.250
JOHN: Well, his life
is going good,

17:54.250 --> 17:55.500
so he’s not going to need it.

17:57.917 --> 18:00.041
Sit down.

18:00.041 --> 18:02.166
You know, I know I haven’t
been really agreeable

18:02.166 --> 18:04.375
about your bohemian lifestyle,

18:04.375 --> 18:08.750
but losing everything just means
you have more to gain.

18:08.750 --> 18:10.250
Without all those distractions,

18:10.250 --> 18:13.417
who knows what
you’re capable of?

18:13.417 --> 18:15.667
-That’s a good point.
-Mhm.

18:15.667 --> 18:19.542
My life can really be
all about focusing on my art.

18:19.542 --> 18:20.542
JOHN: Oh, no, no, no, no.

18:20.542 --> 18:22.542
You got to stop
with that nonsense.

18:22.542 --> 18:25.000
I called a buddy
and I got you a job

18:25.000 --> 18:29.041
with his company
that makes airline snacks.

18:29.041 --> 18:31.250
The pay is peanuts.

18:31.250 --> 18:32.917
Unless you choose pretzels.

18:37.500 --> 18:39.333
WILL: Okay, new guy,
here are the rules.

18:39.333 --> 18:41.000
This is my mug.

18:41.000 --> 18:42.834
What’s the rule?

18:42.834 --> 18:44.291
That’s right, you get it.

18:44.291 --> 18:46.000
And this right here
is my "pube-icle."

18:46.000 --> 18:49.041
"Pube-icle," I copyrighted that,
so same rules as the mug.

18:49.041 --> 18:50.417
I’m sorry, I still
don’t get the rules.

18:50.417 --> 18:51.667
Ah, you’re going
to fit in just fine.

18:51.667 --> 18:55.083
Ooh, Saturday night
at Boomers goes off!

18:55.083 --> 18:56.375
Much like the panties
of the ladies

18:56.375 --> 18:57.875
who work at this establishment.

18:57.875 --> 18:58.917
Oh, wow, huh.

18:58.917 --> 19:00.583
Sounds like you’ve slept
with a lot of coworkers.

19:00.583 --> 19:02.667
Not that many or any,

19:02.667 --> 19:05.000
but I have been laying
a lot of groundwork

19:05.000 --> 19:06.625
over the last 12 years.

19:06.625 --> 19:08.667
It’s like waiting
for a slot machine to pay off,

19:08.667 --> 19:10.667
